1. How many types of conditions are available in conditional formatting on Excel?
In Excel's conditional formatting, there are several types of conditions you can apply. Some common ones include:

Highlight Cells Rules:

Greater Than, Less Than, Between, Equal To, Text That Contains, A Date Occurring, Duplicate Values, etc.
Top/Bottom Rules:

Top 10 Items, Top 10%, Bottom 10 Items, Bottom 10%, Above Average, Below Average, etc.
Data Bars:

Gradient color bars based on cell values.
Color Scales:

Gradient fill based on color scales.
Icon Sets:

Sets of icons based on cell values.
New Rule:

Allows for creating custom formulas and conditions.
2. How to insert border in Excel with Format Cells dialog?
To insert borders in Excel using the Format Cells dialog:

Select Cells:

Highlight the cells or range where you want to apply borders.
Right-Click and Choose Format Cells:

Right-click on the selected cells, choose "Format Cells."
Go to the Border Tab:

In the Format Cells dialog box, go to the "Border" tab.
Choose Border Style:

Select the desired border style (e.g., outline, inside, outside) and adjust line style if needed.
Click OK:

Click "OK" to apply the borders.
3. How to Format Numbers as Currency in Excel?
To format numbers as currency in Excel:

Select Cells:

Highlight the cells or range containing the numbers you want to format.
Go to the Home Tab:

Navigate to the "Home" tab on the ribbon.
Number Group:

In the "Number" group, click on the drop-down arrow next to the Number Format box.
Choose Currency:

From the drop-down menu, select the "Currency" option.
4. What are the steps to format numbers in Excel with the Percent style?
To format numbers in Excel with the Percent style:

Select Cells:

Highlight the cells or range containing the numbers you want to format.
Go to the Home Tab:

Navigate to the "Home" tab on the ribbon.
Number Group:

In the "Number" group, click on the drop-down arrow next to the Number Format box.
Choose Percent:

From the drop-down menu, select the "Percent" option.
5. What is a shortcut to merge two or more cells in Excel?
The shortcut to merge two or more cells in Excel is Alt + H + M + Enter:

Select the cells you want to merge.
Press Alt + H to activate the Home tab.
Press M to select the Merge & Center option.
Press Enter to confirm.
6. How do you use text commands in Excel?
If by "text commands" you mean entering text in Excel:

Entering Text in a Cell:

Click on the cell where you want to enter text and start typing.
Text Functions:

Use text functions like CONCATENATE, LEFT, RIGHT, MID, etc., to manipulate text.
Text Alignment:

Adjust text alignment (left, center, right) using the alignment options in the ribbon.
Text Formatting:

Use formatting options in the ribbon to format text (font, color, style).
Text to Columns:

Use the "Text to Columns" feature under the Data tab to split text into separate columns based on a delimiter.
These actions allow you to work with and manipulate text within Excel.
